{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-post-js","path":"/resting-potential","result":{"data":{"markdownRemark":{"html":"<p>Communication across neurons happens by the means of electric-signals. The electricity is due to the presence of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>N</mi><msup><mi>a</mi><mo lspace=\"0em\" rspace=\"0em\">+</mo></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">Na^{+}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.771331em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">N</span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathdefault\">a</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.771331em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">+</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span>, <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi>K</mi><mo lspace=\"0em\" rspace=\"0em\">+</mo></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">K^{+}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.771331em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathdefault\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">K</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.771331em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">+</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span>, <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>C</mi><msup><mi>a</mi><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>+</mo></mrow></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">Ca^{2+}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8141079999999999em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathdefault\">a</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.8141079999999999em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">2</span><span class=\"mord mtight\">+</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> and <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>C</mi><msup><mi>l</mi><mo lspace=\"0em\" rspace=\"0em\">−</mo></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">Cl^{-}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.771331em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathdefault\" style=\"margin-right:0.01968em;\">l</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.771331em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">−</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> ions. These <em>charges</em> are present around the neurons, separated by a neuron's membrane. This separation creates a <em>potential difference</em>. If a neuron is at rest this <em>potential difference</em> is then called the <em>resting potential</em>.</p>\n<h3 id=\"facts\" style=\"position:relative;\"><a href=\"#facts\" aria-label=\"facts permalink\" class=\"anchor before\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>Facts</h3>\n<ol>\n<li>Charges that cause neural activity: <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>N</mi><msup><mi>a</mi><mo lspace=\"0em\" rspace=\"0em\">+</mo></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">Na^{+}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.771331em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">N</span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathdefault\">a</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.771331em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">+</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span>, <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi>K</mi><mo lspace=\"0em\" rspace=\"0em\">+</mo></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">K^{+}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.771331em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathdefault\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">K</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.771331em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">+</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span>, <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>C</mi><msup><mi>a</mi><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>+</mo></mrow></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">Ca^{2+}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8141079999999999em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathdefault\">a</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.8141079999999999em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">2</span><span class=\"mord mtight\">+</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> and <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>C</mi><msup><mi>l</mi><mo lspace=\"0em\" rspace=\"0em\">−</mo></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">Cl^{-}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.771331em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathdefault\" style=\"margin-right:0.01968em;\">l</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.771331em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">−</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> ions.</li>\n<li>The <em>potential difference</em> of a neuron at rest is called <em>resting potential</em>.</li>\n<li><em>Membrane potential</em> is the voltage across the membrane of a neuron. (values lie between <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo>−</mo><mn>90</mn><mtext>mV</mtext></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">-90\\text{mV}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.76666em;vertical-align:-0.08333em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">−</span><span class=\"mord\">9</span><span class=\"mord\">0</span><span class=\"mord text\"><span class=\"mord\">mV</span></span></span></span></span> <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo>+</mo><mn>60</mn><mtext>mV</mtext></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">+60\\text{mV}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.76666em;vertical-align:-0.08333em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">+</span><span class=\"mord\">6</span><span class=\"mord\">0</span><span class=\"mord text\"><span class=\"mord\">mV</span></span></span></span></span>).</li>\n<li><em>Resting potential</em> is the <em>membrane potential</em> of a neuron at rest. The values are about <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo>−</mo><mn>70</mn><mtext>mV</mtext></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">-70\\text{mV}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.76666em;vertical-align:-0.08333em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">−</span><span class=\"mord\">7</span><span class=\"mord\">0</span><span class=\"mord text\"><span class=\"mord\">mV</span></span></span></span></span>.</li>\n</ol>\n<p>If the outside of a neuron at rest is <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mn>50</mn><mtext>mV</mtext></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">50\\text{mV}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">5</span><span class=\"mord\">0</span><span class=\"mord text\"><span class=\"mord\">mV</span></span></span></span></span> more positive than it's inside, then the <em>membrane potential</em> is <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo>−</mo><mn>50</mn><mrow><mi>m</mi><mi>V</mi></mrow></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">-50{mV}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.76666em;vertical-align:-0.08333em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">−</span><span class=\"mord\">5</span><span class=\"mord\">0</span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathdefault\">m</span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\" style=\"margin-right:0.22222em;\">V</span></span></span></span></span>.</p>\n<h2 id=\"ionic-movement\" style=\"position:relative;\"><a href=\"#ionic-movement\" aria-label=\"ionic movement permalink\" class=\"anchor before\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>Ionic movement</h2>\n<p>So far we have established that neurons have electric charges due to the presence of some ions. We also went through membrane potential and some values that they may have. Let's try to visualize how the charges are acquired.</p>\n<h3 id=\"diffusion\" style=\"position:relative;\"><a href=\"#diffusion\" aria-label=\"diffusion permalink\" class=\"anchor before\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>Diffusion</h3>\n<p>Imagine a liquid in a container. Adding a drop of colour will cause the colour to disperse farther from the point of initial contact in a random fashion. Diffusion defines movement from a region of high concentration to lower concentration. This means at some point the concentration throughout the liquid will be similar at that point the movement would cease.</p>\n<p><figure class=\"gatsby-resp-image-figure\" style=\"\">\n    <span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;  max-width: 690px;\"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/blog/static/f23329315eadb13edc978c0d904df7db/274e1/diffusion.jpg\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 75.14450867052024%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/jpeg;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"Fig: Diffusion of K+ ions, movement from a region of high-concentration (inside the membrane) to low-concentration (outside the membrane).\"\n        title=\"Fig: Diffusion of K+ ions, movement from a region of high-concentration (inside the membrane) to low-concentration (outside the membrane).\"\n        src=\"/blog/static/f23329315eadb13edc978c0d904df7db/15ec7/diffusion.jpg\"\n        srcset=\"/blog/static/f23329315eadb13edc978c0d904df7db/9ac50/diffusion.jpg 173w,\n/blog/static/f23329315eadb13edc978c0d904df7db/8d48c/diffusion.jpg 345w,\n/blog/static/f23329315eadb13edc978c0d904df7db/15ec7/diffusion.jpg 690w,\n/blog/static/f23329315eadb13edc978c0d904df7db/af659/diffusion.jpg 1035w,\n/blog/static/f23329315eadb13edc978c0d904df7db/89b2d/diffusion.jpg 1380w,\n/blog/static/f23329315eadb13edc978c0d904df7db/274e1/diffusion.jpg 2160w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 690px) 100vw, 690px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n      />\n  </a>\n    </span>\n    <figcaption class=\"gatsby-resp-image-figcaption\">Fig: Diffusion of K+ ions, movement from a region of high-concentration (inside the membrane) to low-concentration (outside the membrane).</figcaption>\n  </figure></p>\n<h3 id=\"electrostatic-forces\" style=\"position:relative;\"><a href=\"#electrostatic-forces\" aria-label=\"electrostatic forces permalink\" class=\"anchor before\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>Electrostatic forces</h3>\n<p>Charges can be positive or negative depending on the presence of electrons in the material. If same type of charges are brought together, they will repel each other. Charged materials seek the opposite type of charge to balance their excess or deficit of charge so that they can go back to their non-ionized, natural state.\n<figure class=\"gatsby-resp-image-figure\" style=\"\">\n    <span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;  max-width: 690px;\"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/blog/static/d8fed2073a117883539455c09457b6be/274e1/electrostatics-and-k-plus-ions.jpg\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 75.14450867052024%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/jpeg;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"Fig: Electrostatic effects prevent movement across the ion channel\"\n        title=\"Fig: Electrostatic effects prevent movement across the ion channel\"\n        src=\"/blog/static/d8fed2073a117883539455c09457b6be/15ec7/electrostatics-and-k-plus-ions.jpg\"\n        srcset=\"/blog/static/d8fed2073a117883539455c09457b6be/9ac50/electrostatics-and-k-plus-ions.jpg 173w,\n/blog/static/d8fed2073a117883539455c09457b6be/8d48c/electrostatics-and-k-plus-ions.jpg 345w,\n/blog/static/d8fed2073a117883539455c09457b6be/15ec7/electrostatics-and-k-plus-ions.jpg 690w,\n/blog/static/d8fed2073a117883539455c09457b6be/af659/electrostatics-and-k-plus-ions.jpg 1035w,\n/blog/static/d8fed2073a117883539455c09457b6be/89b2d/electrostatics-and-k-plus-ions.jpg 1380w,\n/blog/static/d8fed2073a117883539455c09457b6be/274e1/electrostatics-and-k-plus-ions.jpg 2160w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 690px) 100vw, 690px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n      />\n  </a>\n    </span>\n    <figcaption class=\"gatsby-resp-image-figcaption\">Fig: Electrostatic effects prevent movement across the ion channel</figcaption>\n  </figure></p>\n<h2 id=\"building-charges\" style=\"position:relative;\"><a href=\"#building-charges\" aria-label=\"building charges permalink\" class=\"anchor before\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>Building charges</h2>\n<p>Let's take a situation of neurons now. If the concentration of say, <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>N</mi><msup><mi>a</mi><mo lspace=\"0em\" rspace=\"0em\">+</mo></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">Na^{+}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.771331em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">N</span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathdefault\">a</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.771331em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">+</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> ions inside the neuron is <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mn>200</mn><mi>m</mi><mi>M</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">200 mM</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">2</span><span class=\"mord\">0</span><span class=\"mord\">0</span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\">m</span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">M</span></span></span></span> while outside the concentration is <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mn>10</mn><mi>m</mi><mi>M</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">10mM</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">1</span><span class=\"mord\">0</span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\">m</span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">M</span></span></span></span>, then diffusion will cause <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>N</mi><msup><mi>a</mi><mo lspace=\"0em\" rspace=\"0em\">+</mo></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">Na^{+}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.771331em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">N</span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathdefault\">a</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.771331em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">+</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> ions to move outside. It should be easy to follow that this will cause the outside of the neuron to slowly get more positively charged. Eventually more charges won't be able to escape from within the neuron because the electrostatic forces will repel the positively charged ions.</p>","timeToRead":2,"excerpt":"Communication across neurons happens by the means of electric-signals. The electricity is due to the presence of , ,  and  ions. These…","frontmatter":{"tit